SIMPLE: prejudice
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Prejudice
<hw>Prej"u*dice</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>pr⟦eacute⟧judice</ets>, L. <ets>praejudicium</ets>; <ets>prae</ets>
before + <ets>judicium</ets> judgment. See <er>Prejudicate</er>,
<er>Judicial</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Foresight.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Naught might hinder his quick <qex>prejudize</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An opinion or judgment formed without due
examination; prejudgment; a leaning toward one side of a question from
other considerations than those belonging to it; an unreasonable
predilection for, or objection against, anything; especially, an opinion
or leaning adverse to anything, without just grounds, or before
sufficient knowledge.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Though often misled by <qex>prejudice</qex> and passion, he was
emphatically an honest man.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A bias on the part of judge, juror,
or witness which interferes with fairness of judgment.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Mischief; hurt; damage; injury; detriment.</def>
<rj><au>Locke.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>England and France might, through their amity,⟦br⟧
Breed him some <qex>prejudice</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Prejudgment; prepossession; bias; harm; hurt;
damage; detriment; mischief; disadvantage.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prejudice</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Prejudice
<hw>Prej"u*dice</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Prejudiced</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Prejudicing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>pr⟦eacute⟧judicier</ets>. See <er>Prejudice</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause to have prejudice; to
prepossess with opinions formed without due knowledge or examination; to
bias the mind of, by hasty and incorrect notions; to give an
unreasonable bent to, as to one side or the other of a cause; <as>as, to
<ex>prejudice</ex> a critic or a juryman</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Suffer not any beloved study to <qex>prejudice</qex> your mind so
far as to despise all other learning.</q> <rj><qau>I.
Watts</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To obstruct or injure by prejudices, or by previous
bias of the mind; hence, generally, to hurt; to damage; to injure; to
impair; <as>as, to <ex>prejudice</ex> a good cause</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Seek how may <qex>prejudice</qex> the foe.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prejudicial</ent>⟦br⟧
